The call for a march from Jamia to Parliament was given by the Jamia Coordination Committee, but scores of locals joined in. The last time Jamia students had called for a march to Parliament on January 30, a student, Shadab Farooq, was shot at by a juvenile.

Around 2 pm, the march reached Holy Family Hospital where heavy police barricades welcomed them. Repeated announcements were made by police telling protesters they did not have permission and should retreat. Some protesters climbed on to police barricades, forcing Meena to climb up as well. Amid the scuffle, water packets â€” both open and unopened â€” were flung by protesters at police.

Around 3 pm, the Chief Proctor made an appeal to students to retreat: â€œYou have registered your protest, now please move back. Donâ€™t get into a confrontation with the police.â€

Meena also took to the mic and told students: â€œPlease go back. You donâ€™t have permission. Your protest has been registered. If there is a memorandum, please submit it to us. We will submit it to the government.â€

Agitated protesters refused to budge, following which the police used â€œmild forceâ€ to push them back. Some protesters fainted due to exertion, while others alleged police brutality.

The scuffle intensified by 6 pm as students refused to budge and a group of protesters gheraoed Sukhdev Vihar police station. Sukhdev Vihar Metro station was also closed off for sometime.

Additional PRO Anil Mittal said a case is being registered against the â€œviolent crowdâ€ under IPC sections 186, 353, 332 and sections related to damage of property. â€œPoliceâ€¦ showed a lot of patience in handling aggressive Jamia students near Holy Family Hospitalâ€¦,â€ he added.

